<graph edgedefault="undirected"><node id="Fish-Borne Trematodes">
  <data key="d0">Fish-Borne Trematodes</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Fish-borne trematodes are a group of parasites belonging to the Opisthorchiidae, Heterophyidae, and Lecithodendriidae families, important from clinical and epidemiological perspectives.&lt;SEP&gt;Parasitic worms whose prevalence in humans and molecular identification were investigated, and were revealed to be distinct groups.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-85aeceedda26a4121170818356b6da95</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768539592</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Opisthorchiidae">
  <data key="d0">Opisthorchiidae</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Opisthorchiidae is a family of fish-borne trematodes, the differentiation of which is important clinically and epidemiologically.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502786</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Heterophyidae">
  <data key="d0">Heterophyidae</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Heterophyidae is a family of fish-borne trematodes, the differentiation of which is important clinically and epidemiologically.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502786</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Lecithodendriidae">
  <data key="d0">Lecithodendriidae</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Lecithodendriidae is a family of fish-borne trematodes, the differentiation of which is important clinically and epidemiologically.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502786</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Clinical Perspective">
  <data key="d0">Clinical Perspective</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The clinical perspective highlights the importance of differentiating fish-borne trematodes for medical diagnosis and treatment.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502786</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Epidemiological Perspective">
  <data key="d0">Epidemiological Perspective</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The epidemiological perspective emphasizes the importance of differentiating fish-borne trematodes for understanding disease patterns and control.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502786</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Epidemiological Investigation">
  <data key="d0">Epidemiological Investigation</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Epidemiological investigation is the process of studying disease patterns and prevalence, which currently relies on morphological examination of adult worms.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502786</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Conventional Parasitological Detection Techniques">
  <data key="d0">Conventional Parasitological Detection Techniques</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Conventional parasitological detection techniques are traditional methods for identifying parasite eggs in faeces, such as microscopy, which are insufficient for differentiating morphologically similar trematode eggs.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502786</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Trematode Eggs">
  <data key="d0">Trematode Eggs</data>
  <data key="d1">naturalobject</data>
  <data key="d2">Trematode eggs are the reproductive stage of trematodes, which are morphologically similar across different species, making differentiation difficult for conventional techniques.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502786</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Adult Worms">
  <data key="d0">Adult Worms</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Adult worms are the mature stage of trematodes, whose morphological examination after expulsion chemotherapy is currently relied upon for epidemiological investigation.&lt;SEP&gt;The mature stage of Haplorchis pumilio found in the small intestine of infected foxes, quantified at the end of the study.&lt;SEP&gt;The mature stage of the liver fluke from which morphological features were observed for identification.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-13eb735a93b91be4933bcef865387615&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-879b5135aa54452de1963b365453a951</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768539675</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Expulsion Chemotherapy">
  <data key="d0">Expulsion Chemotherapy</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Expulsion chemotherapy is a medical treatment used to expel adult worms from infected individuals, enabling their morphological examination.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502787</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="PCR Test">
  <data key="d0">PCR Test</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The PCR test is a molecular diagnostic method developed and evaluated to amplify a specific segment of ribosomal DNA from opisthorchiid and heterophyid fluke eggs directly from faeces.&lt;SEP&gt;A recently developed test method used for the detection of Opisthorchis Viverrini in human faecal samples.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e78ffab293d85b4ebff1564e0a3f2c3c</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768543303</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Internal Transcribed Spacer Region">
  <data key="d0">Internal Transcribed Spacer Region</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The internal transcribed spacer region is a specific segment of ribosomal DNA that the PCR test is designed to amplify for fluke identification.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502787</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Ribosomal DNA">
  <data key="d0">Ribosomal DNA</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Ribosomal DNA is the genetic material containing the internal transcribed spacer region targeted by the PCR test.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502787</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Opisthorchiid Flukes">
  <data key="d0">Opisthorchiid Flukes</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Opisthorchiid flukes are a type of trematode whose eggs can be detected by the developed PCR test and from which DNA was amplified.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502787</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Heterophyid Flukes">
  <data key="d0">Heterophyid Flukes</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Heterophyid flukes are a type of trematode whose eggs can be detected by the developed PCR test.&lt;SEP&gt;Heterophyid flukes are several species of flukes indicated to be endemic in two riverside localities.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6227d854559ab8d6412ebf0a9615a949</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768542197</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Faeces">
  <data key="d0">Faeces</data>
  <data key="d1">naturalobject</data>
  <data key="d2">Faeces are biological samples from which trematode eggs can be directly taken for PCR testing or detected by conventional techniques.&lt;SEP&gt;This is a biological sample collected from dogs, used for the detection of small trematode eggs.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3991fe2061a752f9eb776d3fcc681c33</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768542048</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Rural Community In Central Thailand">
  <data key="d0">Rural Community In Central Thailand</data>
  <data key="d1">location</data>
  <data key="d2">A rural community in central Thailand served as the evaluation site for the PCR test and where infection prevalence was studied.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502787</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="DNA Amplification Quantity">
  <data key="d0">DNA Amplification Quantity</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">DNA amplification quantity refers to the lowest amount of DNA (in picograms) that could be amplified from individual adult trematodes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502788</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Opisthorchis Viverrini">
  <data key="d0">Opisthorchis Viverrini</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Opisthorchis viverrini is a specific species of opisthorchiid liver fluke, with a lowest amplifiable DNA quantity of 0.6 pg, identified as infecting individuals.&lt;SEP&gt;The specific species name identified for the small liver fluke.&lt;SEP&gt;Opisthorchis viverrini is an organism whose Mitochondrial Cytochrome C Oxidase Subunit I (CO I) gene and Second Internal Transcribed Spacer Region (ITS II) gene were studied.&lt;SEP&gt;A specific parasitic organism that the PCR test is designed to detect in human faecal samples.&lt;SEP&gt;A parasite whose detection in experimentally infected hamsters is the target of the PCR-based method.&lt;SEP&gt;A specific type of parasite that 681 residents were previously found positive for.&lt;SEP&gt;Opisthorchis viverrini is a type of fluke whose density-dependent fecundity in humans is studied in the journal article.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-879b5135aa54452de1963b365453a951&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-52a9c5f1506ae9dbf3a1f1866bd28763&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e78ffab293d85b4ebff1564e0a3f2c3c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-756a1dc033c87aa1df4886cc248f2102&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4e38bf3bf822086eb0e754ae3929ef24&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2eeaa3f96c5a6e0b0b9e3c585764f59a</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768544567</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Clonorchis Sinensis">
  <data key="d0">Clonorchis Sinensis</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Clonorchis sinensis is a specific species of liver fluke, with a lowest amplifiable DNA quantity of 0.8 pg, identified as infecting individuals, and an endemic community was reported.&lt;SEP&gt;Clonorchis Sinensis (CS) is a parasitic organism whose infection states were evaluated in patients, and whose eggs are detected for diagnosing clonorchiasis.&lt;SEP&gt;Clonorchis Sinensis is a species of trematode, closely related to O. viverrini, that does not cross-react with the PCR method.&lt;SEP&gt;Clonorchis Sinensis is a parasite that utilizes a large amount of external glucose for its energy metabolism.&lt;SEP&gt;A parasitic organism whose DNA is the target of detection in patient samples.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-acad4a812e7cbf80eff3b268dbc2646a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-18e589c37865ab506d25c271a1ebeb47&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bf15a731bb0c2f9e6459d16f803c76e1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c1aaa2470e7464a09774dbb42c1287e6</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768544005</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Haplorchis Taichui">
  <data key="d0">Haplorchis Taichui</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Haplorchis taichui is a specific species of intestinal fluke, with a lowest amplifiable DNA quantity of 3 pg.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502788</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Mixed Infection">
  <data key="d0">Mixed Infection</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Mixed infection is the co-occurrence of multiple fluke species in a single individual, which the PCR test was capable of detecting experimentally.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502788</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Sanamchaikaet District">
  <data key="d0">Sanamchaikaet District</data>
  <data key="d1">location</data>
  <data key="d2">Sanamchaikaet district is a specific rural community in central Thailand where 11.6% of individuals tested positive for 'Opisthorchis-like' eggs.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502788</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="'Opisthorchis-Like' Eggs">
  <data key="d0">'Opisthorchis-Like' Eggs</data>
  <data key="d1">naturalobject</data>
  <data key="d2">'Opisthorchis-like' eggs are trematode eggs detected in faeces using conventional parasitological techniques, which may belong to various Opisthorchis-related species.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502788</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Microscopy">
  <data key="d0">Microscopy</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Microscopy is a conventional parasitological detection technique used as a comparative method to evaluate the sensitivity and specificity of the PCR test.&lt;SEP&gt;Microscopy is a diagnostic method, where immediate microscopy after a positive dipstick test was found to improve diagnostic efficiency.&lt;SEP&gt;A diagnostic method used for identifying schistosomiasis cases.&lt;SEP&gt;Microscopy is a diagnostic method that was unable to discriminate between O. viverrini and H. taichui infections.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0f16d7b93cdaec3ff0b234ee22d42546&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8934b8f0f1a6ea64c03497182e856f1b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b5b7e73380988eeb174ca3b789fd0d66</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768544214</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="PCR Sensitivity">
  <data key="d0">PCR Sensitivity</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">PCR sensitivity is the measure of the PCR test's ability to correctly identify true positive infections, reported as 71.0% compared to microscopy.&lt;SEP&gt;A previously reported characteristic or performance metric of the PCR test, which was not supported by the current evaluation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e78ffab293d85b4ebff1564e0a3f2c3c</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768543303</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="PCR Specificity">
  <data key="d0">PCR Specificity</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">PCR specificity is the measure of the PCR test's ability to correctly identify true negative infections, reported as 76.7% compared to microscopy.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502789</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Microscopy-Positive PCR Products">
  <data key="d0">Microscopy-Positive PCR Products</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Microscopy-positive PCR products refer to the results from PCR tests performed on samples previously identified as positive by microscopy, used for species identification.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502789</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Didymozoidae Eggs">
  <data key="d0">Didymozoidae Eggs</data>
  <data key="d1">naturalobject</data>
  <data key="d2">Didymozoidae eggs are trematode eggs identified in some individuals, presumed to be passed mechanically after ingestion of infected fishes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502789</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Infected Fishes">
  <data key="d0">Infected Fishes</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Infected fishes are the presumed source of Didymozoidae eggs ingested by individuals.&lt;SEP&gt;Fishes that host metacercariae, which are detectable by the multiplex PCR approach.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-73c7f0c924eada8686a75bb4a92f7f4f</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768542582</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="C. Sinensis-Endemic Community">
  <data key="d0">C. Sinensis-Endemic Community</data>
  <data key="d1">location</data>
  <data key="d2">A C. sinensis-endemic community is a population group identified in central Thailand where Clonorchis sinensis infection is prevalent, representing the first report for the region.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502789</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Liver Fluke Species">
  <data key="d0">Liver Fluke Species</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Liver fluke species are a type of trematode, including Opisthorchis viverrini and Clonorchis sinensis, that infect the liver and can be specifically identified by the PCR test.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502789</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Intestinal Fluke Species">
  <data key="d0">Intestinal Fluke Species</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Intestinal fluke species are a type of trematode, such as Haplorchis taichui, that infect the intestines and can be specifically identified by the PCR test.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768502789</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Epidemiological Surveys">
  <data key="d0">Epidemiological Surveys</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Epidemiological surveys are future investigations where the developed PCR test will serve as an important tool for the specific identification of liver and intestinal fluke species.&lt;SEP&gt;Epidemiological surveys are a research method used for detecting specific parasite stages and studying infections in fish hosts.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3d9595b06856e474a44aa9b2a3ed95a7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538873</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Southeast Asia">
  <data key="d0">Southeast Asia</data>
  <data key="d1">location</data>
  <data key="d2">Southeast Asia is the broader geographical region whose known range for Clonorchis sinensis is extended by the study's finding of a C. sinensis-endemic community in central Thailand.&lt;SEP&gt;A geographical region where infections with fish-borne zoonotic trematodes are highly prevalent.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-13eb735a93b91be4933bcef865387615</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768515475</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Study">
  <data key="d0">Study</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The Study refers to the current research described in the text, which includes findings such as the identification and first report of a C. sinensis-endemic community.&lt;SEP&gt;A study is a piece of research or investigation, with 118 studies meeting inclusion criteria in this review, evaluating various diagnostic approaches for haematuria.&lt;SEP&gt;An investigation or research effort where the small liver fluke was found.&lt;SEP&gt;The study involved comparing diagnostic methods for stool samples in 1,727 persons from Anhui Province, China.&lt;SEP&gt;A research effort that indicated findings about a newly developed infectious bursal disease vaccine.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0f16d7b93cdaec3ff0b234ee22d42546&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-879b5135aa54452de1963b365453a951&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-238c2e1b073d66f94b56266ab745be34&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8e6a0c54d176872c8e2cb5eb5bad7b83</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768545475</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Individuals">
  <data key="d0">Individuals</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Individuals refers to the people in the rural communities who were tested for trematode infections in this study.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-97107d438f9f6fb6338f2e1ee3562995</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
