</node>
<node id="Schistosoma Japonicum">
  <data key="d0">Schistosoma Japonicum</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Schistosoma japonicum is a parasitic worm endemic in the Philippines, China, and Indonesia, infecting over 40 mammalian host species and causing schistosomiasis.&lt;SEP&gt;Schistosoma japonicum is a parasite whose transmission is the target of a national program and diagnostic efforts.&lt;SEP&gt;Schistosoma japonicum is a parasite transmitted to humans, causing Schistosomiasis japonica.&lt;SEP&gt;Schistosoma Japonicum is a parasitic worm that causes infection in humans.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c33d09b8957ec6de1ecb70a00240f29b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fb64e8269ca7a83eae32849920a5e03b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2080ebaf27fa02a0282964a7c0f555bb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0024b8ddacb751e7c5dc5f8d0ea108eb</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768543728</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Philippines">
  <data key="d0">Philippines</data>
  <data key="d1">location</data>
  <data key="d2">The Philippines is a country where Schistosoma japonicum is endemic, and the role of carabao in its transmission is being investigated.&lt;SEP&gt;The country where S. Japonicum infection in water buffaloes and its transmission to humans are observed.&lt;SEP&gt;A country where clinical/pathophysiological studies are supported by Wellcome Trust and AFRIMS.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c33d09b8957ec6de1ecb70a00240f29b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-12418866e7efdfc1aa9ada51674dfa7e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-09f7b30a7a44fb488c4648dd1aaa96dc</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768547196</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="China">
  <data key="d0">China</data>
  <data key="d1">location</data>
  <data key="d2">China is a country that confronts significant public health challenges, particularly concerning *Schistosomiasis japonica*, which remains a major public health problem. *Schistosoma japonicum* is endemic throughout the country, with water buffaloes recognized as major reservoirs of human infection. Despite this persistent issue, China has made remarkable progress in reducing human *Schistosoma japonicum* infections. Given the ongoing need for improved disease management, China is identified as a priority area for the development and application of better diagnostic tests, especially for use in field situations.

Beyond parasitic diseases, China has also been affected by the spread of Infectious Bursal Disease Virus (IBDV), which began in the early 1990s. The prevalence and genotypes of this virus were subjects of study within China from 2019 to 2020. Geographically, China is the country where Anhui Province is located. Additionally, China is a country where the validation and potential adoption of a specific questionnaire are currently being considered.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c33d09b8957ec6de1ecb70a00240f29b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ab8696e0621fb10013bbe66408ec389f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-66b9c03397d1767f2c8fe38e229f4281&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2080ebaf27fa02a0282964a7c0f555bb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2bf098bc854474022cb038b7b5f5356f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-238c2e1b073d66f94b56266ab745be34&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eba29f70e52c3514cfb16d8cf1c63f59&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fd6f47c15d875994d5ea11165b04ac73</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768543659</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Indonesia">
  <data key="d0">Indonesia</data>
  <data key="d1">location</data>
  <data key="d2">Indonesia is a country where Schistosoma japonicum is endemic.</data>
