  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="ELISA">
  <data key="d0">ELISA</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">ELISA, or Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay, is a widely used laboratory, immunological, and biochemical method primarily employed for analyzing biological samples. It functions as a method of investigation, particularly for diagnostic purposes. Its applications extend to seroepidemiologic studies, assessing the impact of chemotherapy, and serving as a serodiagnostic method.

ELISA has been specifically evaluated for its diagnostic capabilities in various contexts. For instance, it is used for the specific detection of IgG4 with rCsCatL-propeptide and is also utilized with Soluble Egg Antigen (SEA). As an immunoassay method, ELISA is instrumental in the diagnosis of schistosomiasis japonica, demonstrating the capability to either rule in or rule out the diagnosis.

While a valuable diagnostic test, there is a recognized need for improvement in the conventional form of ELISA. Its diagnostic performance has, in certain comparisons, been described as being inferior to other methods, such as the Indirect Hemagglutination Assay (IHA).&lt;SEP&gt;ELISA (Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay) is a laboratory method used to assess the sensitivity and specificity of antigens in diagnostic assays.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f0d92923951ea02d5bee6d00bab160af&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-741c138905578052bbea5e72d3ce9cf7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c4f0a5936dcb5c74c221d4f619d8f45a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-794b1d58cb9a774ddce4478b53693842&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-45a11ad2880b7620ce20fe29f1134147&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9c16494a7ac3bbc4464e0d0259e38ec6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eba29f70e52c3514cfb16d8cf1c63f59&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5de9a9ca2de0925c1a3c20cd63a2ec57&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0fb7b6058a75fb52450283f2bfbbb406</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768543838</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Soluble Egg Antigen (SEA)">
  <data key="d0">Soluble Egg Antigen (SEA)</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Soluble Egg Antigen (SEA) is an antigen used with ELISA in studies, the reactivity of which did not modify one year after treatment.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f0d92923951ea02d5bee6d00bab160af</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768515106</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Seroepidemiologic Studies">
  <data key="d0">Seroepidemiologic Studies</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Seroepidemiologic Studies are a type of epidemiologic study for which COPT, intradermal test, and ELISA with SEA are evaluated as diagnostic tools.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f0d92923951ea02d5bee6d00bab160af</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768515106</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Chemotherapy">
  <data key="d0">Chemotherapy</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Chemotherapy is a medical treatment whose impact must be assessed using diagnostic tests like COPT and ELISA.&lt;SEP&gt;Chemotherapy is a medical treatment method for infections, after which the surveillance of cure is conducted.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f0d92923951ea02d5bee6d00bab160af&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6637a4ff732a42270c95a322eb3e4fc6</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538575</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Treatment">
  <data key="d0">Treatment</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Treatment refers to the medical intervention administered to persons for schistosomiasis, after which their progress and test utility are evaluated.&lt;SEP&gt;A medical intervention applied to target individuals.&lt;SEP&gt;A medical intervention after which cure rates and symptom abatement were observed in children and adults.&lt;SEP&gt;Treatment is a medical intervention administered for a condition or disease.&lt;SEP&gt;Treatment is a medical procedure that, when absent with subsequent salt purgation, contributes to the low sensitivity of the conventional method.&lt;SEP&gt;The management and care of a patient to combat a disease or disorder, facilitated by the PCR assay.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f0d92923951ea02d5bee6d00bab160af&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4d3bc18d8e54a218be10807e3843a0a2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-db9c5e541d976adda7f977a0e6632e65&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27cb4a5bb97ef3dfcbc5e83b0f45a8c4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f216879d0e44c8d03b9d04323edd5fbe&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c1aaa2470e7464a09774dbb42c1287e6</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768544005</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="165 Persons">
  <data key="d0">165 Persons</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">One hundred sixty five persons were followed up for 3, 6, 9, and 12 months after treatment for schistosomiasis.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f0d92923951ea02d5bee6d00bab160af</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768515106</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Age Groups">
  <data key="d0">Age Groups</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Age Groups are classifications used to study the mean sensitivity of COPT among the population.&lt;SEP&gt;Age groups are demographic categories (e.g., 30-39 years) used to analyze variations in the Clonorchis Sinensis egg positive rate among patients.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f0d92923951ea02d5bee6d00bab160af&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-acad4a812e7cbf80eff3b268dbc2646a</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768515552</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Children">
  <data key="d0">Children</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Children showed the highest reactivity to COPT among the studied population.&lt;SEP&gt;A demographic group that was cured less often and experienced slower abatement of symptomatology after treatment compared to adults.&lt;SEP&gt;Children are the subject demographic of the study, specifically regarding their bed net use and hospitalization with DHF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f0d92923951ea02d5bee6d00bab160af&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-db9c5e541d976adda7f977a0e6632e65&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-18dc28b186b69b4dc32fd45ae507f576</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768546725</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Schistosoma Mansoni">
  <data key="d0">Schistosoma Mansoni</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Schistosoma Mansoni is a parasite whose egg fractions are a target for research to isolate components whose antibodies disappear after treatment.&lt;SEP&gt;Schistosoma Mansoni is a type of trematode that infected mice.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f0d92923951ea02d5bee6d00bab160af&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-db410740acd4c96d2a55cda957a5c3b1</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768539213</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Eggs of Schistosoma Mansoni">
  <data key="d0">Eggs of Schistosoma Mansoni</data>
  <data key="d1">naturalobject</data>
  <data key="d2">Eggs of Schistosoma Mansoni are parasitic eggs, from which fractions should be isolated due to the disappearance of their associated antibodies after treatment.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f0d92923951ea02d5bee6d00bab160af</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768515106</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Non Cure Group">
  <data key="d0">Non Cure Group</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The Non Cure Group refers to a subset of treated individuals where COPT reactivity diminished but never fell below 20%.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f0d92923951ea02d5bee6d00bab160af</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768515106</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Research Effort">
  <data key="d0">Research Effort</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Research effort is directed towards isolating specific fractions of Schistosoma mansoni eggs.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f0d92923951ea02d5bee6d00bab160af</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768515106</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Antibodies">
  <data key="d0">Antibodies</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Antibodies are immune proteins associated with fractions of eggs of Schistosoma mansoni, which are expected to disappear after effective treatment.&lt;SEP&gt;Biological markers that are detected to indicate the presence of S. Japonicum.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f0d92923951ea02d5bee6d00bab160af&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-213dd01df1213177a022c154bb9c179e</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
