</node>
<node id="Target Populations">
  <data key="d0">Target Populations</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Target populations are specific groups identified for screening in schistosome-endemic areas using immunodiagnostic techniques.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-6637a4ff732a42270c95a322eb3e4fc6</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538575</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Schistosome-Endemic Areas">
  <data key="d0">Schistosome-Endemic Areas</data>
  <data key="d1">location</data>
  <data key="d2">Schistosome-endemic areas are geographical locations where schistosome infections are prevalent, requiring epidemiological screening and control.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-6637a4ff732a42270c95a322eb3e4fc6</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538575</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Infection Transmission">
  <data key="d0">Infection Transmission</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Infection transmission refers to the spread of infection, which requires periodic control after elimination in an area.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-6637a4ff732a42270c95a322eb3e4fc6</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538575</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="PCR-Positive Tests">
  <data key="d0">PCR-Positive Tests</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A diagnostic method that identified several cases, some of which were judged parasite negative by the parasitological method, demonstrating an advantage in diagnosing light infections.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0249202b2e04fa514eaaf4e2c303acea</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538598</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Parasitological Method">
  <data key="d0">Parasitological Method</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A diagnostic method used to judge cases as parasite negative, contrasting with PCR-positive tests.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0249202b2e04fa514eaaf4e2c303acea</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538598</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Diagnosis">
  <data key="d0">Diagnosis</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The process of identifying a disease or condition, specifically highlighted as where PCR-positive tests show an advantage for light infections.&lt;SEP&gt;Diagnosis is the process of identifying a disease or condition based on its symptoms and signs.&lt;SEP&gt;Diagnosis refers to the process of identifying a condition, which DIGFA facilitates rapidly and accurately for S. japonicum.&lt;SEP&gt;The process of identifying C. sinensis infestation.&lt;SEP&gt;The process or outcome of identifying a disease, which can be ruled in or out using methods like ELISA and IHA.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0249202b2e04fa514eaaf4e2c303acea&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c4f0a5936dcb5c74c221d4f619d8f45a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8b42fd47496d3efb4bab267564a345d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-672eae254cb0547aa2c85fafcd22f7ed&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5de9a9ca2de0925c1a3c20cd63a2ec57</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768543389</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Quantitative Faecal Egg Count">
  <data key="d0">Quantitative Faecal Egg Count</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">The result of a laboratory method used to measure the number of eggs in faeces, showing a correlation with worm recovery.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ad77c043b59272c028c58fbd6263f39a</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538644</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Stoll's Dilution Technique">
  <data key="d0">Stoll's Dilution Technique</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A specific laboratory method used for performing the quantitative faecal egg count.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ad77c043b59272c028c58fbd6263f39a</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538644</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Number Of Worms Recovered">
  <data key="d0">Number Of Worms Recovered</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">The count of parasitic worms found or extracted, which correlates with the quantitative faecal egg count.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ad77c043b59272c028c58fbd6263f39a</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538644</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Eggs Per Gram Of Faeces (epg)">
  <data key="d0">Eggs Per Gram Of Faeces (epg)</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">A unit of measurement indicating the number of parasitic eggs per gram of faecal material, strongly associated with worm burden.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ad77c043b59272c028c58fbd6263f39a</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538644</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Worm Burden">
  <data key="d0">Worm Burden</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The total parasitic load within a host organism, which shows a strong linear association with eggs per gram of faeces.&lt;SEP&gt;A diagnostic indicator, representing a measure of parasitic load, used to obtain diagnoses that showed high concordant results with PCR and FECT.&lt;SEP&gt;Worm burden is an estimation of the number of parasitic worms in a host.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ad77c043b59272c028c58fbd6263f39a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-30162a1defec7ca71236fd24fbcef8a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a6500245b9c6a3adbab9eff0d466b840</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768543279</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="LAMP Assay">
  <data key="d0">LAMP Assay</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The LAMP assay is a molecular diagnostic method proven to be 100 times more sensitive than conventional polymerase chain reaction for the detection of C. sinensis.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3b705a5fd7926bdff4ad166343047ed4</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538684</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Polymerase Chain Reaction">
  <data key="d0">Polymerase Chain Reaction</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR) is a conventional molecular diagnostic method used for detection, referenced here for its comparative sensitivity to the LAMP assay.&lt;SEP&gt;Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR) is a molecular biological method used for the identification of species.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3b705a5fd7926bdff4ad166343047ed4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f5e1f2dee82e2dc7f5380db27c0f1785</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768542615</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="C. Sinensis">
  <data key="d0">C. Sinensis</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">C. sinensis is a parasitic organism detected in fish, which is relevant to the control of human clonorchiasis.&lt;SEP&gt;C. sinensis is the organism associated with the infections that are detected and quantified by real-time PCR in this study.&lt;SEP&gt;A specific organism that can be detected using the Nested PCR Method.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3b705a5fd7926bdff4ad166343047ed4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fe1dcb64ac7b7d66a76a6ee4e711f995&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c71b2b7d263cbd0f9713a997f17fdccd</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768543489</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Fish">
  <data key="d0">Fish</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Fish is a natural object that can host C. sinensis, making it a subject of detection efforts.&lt;SEP&gt;Fish are aquatic animals that commonly host trematodes and are subject to quarantining.&lt;SEP&gt;Organisms in which high parasite prevalence was recorded.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3b705a5fd7926bdff4ad166343047ed4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-18e589c37865ab506d25c271a1ebeb47&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-574cfb1f85240b99afc02b339e81d451</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768542271</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Human Clonorchiasis">
  <data key="d0">Human Clonorchiasis</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Human clonorchiasis is a medical condition or disease, the effective control of which has important implications from improved detection methods.&lt;SEP&gt;Human clonorchiasis is a disease for which recombinant CsLPAP is suggested as a valuable tool in its serodiagnosis.&lt;SEP&gt;Human Clonorchiasis is a parasitic disease affecting humans, for which improved serodiagnosis is being sought.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3b705a5fd7926bdff4ad166343047ed4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0fb7b6058a75fb52450283f2bfbbb406&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-28cc119818cb1eb25c7d4da79213927c</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768543869</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="PCR Method">
  <data key="d0">PCR Method</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The PCR method is described as being specific to O. viverrini and has potential application in fish quarantining, with no cross-reaction with other trematodes.&lt;SEP&gt;A diagnostic method that demonstrated higher sensitivity than the egg-count method in all infected groups, particularly in light infections, and was successfully used to monitor a therapeutic study.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-18e589c37865ab506d25c271a1ebeb47&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8d75398e966dd76ff6a58656562d2c1a</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768542665</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="O. viverrini">
  <data key="d0">O. viverrini</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">O. viverrini is a species of trematode that the PCR method is specific to.&lt;SEP&gt;O. viverrini is a parasitic organism that is highly endemic in all countries of the Lower Mekong Basin despite decades of treatment and control programs.&lt;SEP&gt;O. viverrini is an organism, likely a parasite, whose infection requires differential diagnosis.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-18e589c37865ab506d25c271a1ebeb47&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a240600eef5258b3daf148adf8e8087a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b5b7e73380988eeb174ca3b789fd0d66</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768544214</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Fish Quarantining">
  <data key="d0">Fish Quarantining</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Fish quarantining is a process that represents a potential application for the PCR method.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-18e589c37865ab506d25c271a1ebeb47</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538714</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Trematodes">
  <data key="d0">Trematodes</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Trematodes are a type of parasitic flatworm commonly found in fish, with which the PCR method shows no cross-reaction.&lt;SEP&gt;Trematodes are a class of parasitic flatworms, whose infections can potentially compromise the diagnostic quality of rOvESP.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-18e589c37865ab506d25c271a1ebeb47&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-db410740acd4c96d2a55cda957a5c3b1</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768539214</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Immunoprecipitation Data">
  <data key="d0">Immunoprecipitation Data</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Immunoprecipitation Data is information obtained through immunoprecipitation, used in conjunction with ELISA to draw conclusions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-741c138905578052bbea5e72d3ce9cf7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538803</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Hamster">
  <data key="d0">Hamster</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">A hamster is an animal that serves as a host for a parasitic infection.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-741c138905578052bbea5e72d3ce9cf7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538803</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Hepatobiliary System">
  <data key="d0">Hepatobiliary System</data>
  <data key="d1">naturalobject</data>
  <data key="d2">The Hepatobiliary System is a biological system within the hamster that is infected by a parasite.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-741c138905578052bbea5e72d3ce9cf7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538803</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Parasite">
  <data key="d0">Parasite</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">A parasite is an organism that infects the hamster's hepatobiliary system but does not typically invade host tissue.&lt;SEP&gt;An organism suggested to have a widespread and massive presence in the area.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-741c138905578052bbea5e72d3ce9cf7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-574cfb1f85240b99afc02b339e81d451</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768542271</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Infection">
  <data key="d0">Infection</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Infection is the state of the hamster's hepatobiliary system being infected by a parasite.&lt;SEP&gt;The state of being infected with S. japonicum, detectable in animals.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-741c138905578052bbea5e72d3ce9cf7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e469ec2af24bbc690574902269eceff1</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768544113</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Host Tissue">
  <data key="d0">Host Tissue</data>
  <data key="d1">naturalobject</data>
  <data key="d2">Host Tissue refers to the biological tissue of the host, which the parasite does not normally invade.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-741c138905578052bbea5e72d3ce9cf7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538803</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Systemic Antibody Synthesis">
  <data key="d0">Systemic Antibody Synthesis</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Systemic Antibody Synthesis is the process of producing antibodies throughout the body in response to an infection.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-741c138905578052bbea5e72d3ce9cf7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538803</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Local Antibody Synthesis">
  <data key="d0">Local Antibody Synthesis</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Local Antibody Synthesis is the process of producing antibodies in a specific area, such as the site of infection, which includes IgG and IgA antibody isotypes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-741c138905578052bbea5e72d3ce9cf7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538803</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="IgG Antibody Isotypes">
  <data key="d0">IgG Antibody Isotypes</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">IgG Antibody Isotypes are a specific class of antibodies, included in local antibody synthesis.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-741c138905578052bbea5e72d3ce9cf7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538803</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="IgA Antibody Isotypes">
  <data key="d0">IgA Antibody Isotypes</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">IgA Antibody Isotypes are a specific class of antibodies, included in local antibody synthesis.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-741c138905578052bbea5e72d3ce9cf7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538803</data>
