<node id="PCR-Based Diagnostics">
  <data key="d0">PCR-Based Diagnostics</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">PCR-based diagnostics are diagnostic methods that utilize Polymerase Chain Reaction to identify diseases.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-04e148a1039e18d7262fc9c5d047f8ab</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538840</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Dilemma of Underestimating Disease Burden">
  <data key="d0">Dilemma of Underestimating Disease Burden</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">This dilemma refers to the challenge of accurately assessing the true impact of a disease.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-04e148a1039e18d7262fc9c5d047f8ab</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538840</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="True Burden of Disease">
  <data key="d0">True Burden of Disease</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The true burden of disease represents the actual total impact of a disease, which can be underestimated.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-04e148a1039e18d7262fc9c5d047f8ab</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538840</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Faecal Egg Excretion">
  <data key="d0">Faecal Egg Excretion</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Faecal egg excretion is a measurable indicator among infected individuals.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-04e148a1039e18d7262fc9c5d047f8ab</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538840</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Infected Individuals">
  <data key="d0">Infected Individuals</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Individuals who are carrying a disease.&lt;SEP&gt;Infected Individuals are a proportion of people who exhibit liver fluke worm burden and biliary tract disease due to Opisthorchis.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-04e148a1039e18d7262fc9c5d047f8ab&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-52c7d758a4d4a5daadf2e5a9de45e90d</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768542736</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Large-Scale Use">
  <data key="d0">Large-Scale Use</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Large-scale use refers to the widespread application or deployment of diagnostics.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-04e148a1039e18d7262fc9c5d047f8ab</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538840</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Costs">
  <data key="d0">Costs</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Costs are the financial expenses associated with the implementation and use of PCR-based diagnostics.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-04e148a1039e18d7262fc9c5d047f8ab</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538840</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Experience">
  <data key="d0">Experience</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Experience refers to the practical knowledge and expertise required for using PCR-based diagnostics.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-04e148a1039e18d7262fc9c5d047f8ab</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538840</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="PCR-RFLP Profiles">
  <data key="d0">PCR-RFLP Profiles</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">PCR-RFLP profiles are a type of molecular data that might be useful for diagnosing infections and detecting specific life stages of organisms.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3d9595b06856e474a44aa9b2a3ed95a7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538873</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="O. Taichui">
  <data key="d0">O. Taichui</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">O. Taichui is an organism, likely a parasite, that can cause mixed infections.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3d9595b06856e474a44aa9b2a3ed95a7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538873</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Endemic Areas">
  <data key="d0">Endemic Areas</data>
  <data key="d1">location</data>
  <data key="d2">Endemic areas are geographical locations where mixed O. Taichui infections are prevalent.&lt;SEP&gt;Endemic Areas are geographical regions where infections are regularly found and where control programs are implemented.&lt;SEP&gt;Endemic areas are geographical regions where specific diseases, such as O. viverrini and intestinal fluke infections, are consistently present.&lt;SEP&gt;Geographical regions where patients are located and where clonorchiasis and/or opisthorchiasis are prevalent.&lt;SEP&gt;Endemic areas are geographical regions where epidemiological studies of HIFs are conducted.&lt;SEP&gt;Geographic regions where the transmission status of clonorchiasis is evaluated.&lt;SEP&gt;Endemic Areas are geographical regions where schistosomiasis cases are prevalent, and where the clinical diagnosis of these cases was assessed for sensitivity of diagnostic methods.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3d9595b06856e474a44aa9b2a3ed95a7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-89f546be997c645dad9cafdf67d93b0e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2ff3100b16229e55507c0da581d4f787&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-73c7f0c924eada8686a75bb4a92f7f4f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5b81d6f2dc280c4a251fe3d7c991c9d6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c71b2b7d263cbd0f9713a997f17fdccd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-80b97f9e924421f7263d201cc76d061b</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768544326</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Metacercariae Of O. Viverrini">
  <data key="d0">Metacercariae Of O. Viverrini</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Metacercariae of O. viverrini are a specific life stage of the O. viverrini organism, detectable in epidemiological surveys.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3d9595b06856e474a44aa9b2a3ed95a7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538873</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="O. Viverrini">
  <data key="d0">O. Viverrini</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">O. viverrini is an organism, likely a parasite, whose metacercariae are detected in epidemiological surveys.&lt;SEP&gt;O. viverrini is a species for which a specific DNA probe was constructed.&lt;SEP&gt;O. viverrini is an organism for which co-endemicity can affect the interpretation of DDIA results.&lt;SEP&gt;O. viverrini is a type of parasite found in endemic areas, for which differential diagnosis is important.&lt;SEP&gt;O. viverrini is an organism that is endemic to certain regions or countries and can cause opisthorchiasis and trematodiasis.&lt;SEP&gt;O. viverrini is a species of fluke indicated to be endemic in two riverside localities.&lt;SEP&gt;An organism that produces the 89-kD protein and has the 16 kD antigen as a specific somatic component.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3d9595b06856e474a44aa9b2a3ed95a7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4f9c114fc3d1c11b46a430c5a032db4a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-97e6cdb4d02fc715d7dc1ee3e9c2a50e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2ff3100b16229e55507c0da581d4f787&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f4ca9c4f44e888a9a6574f84b313e13f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6227d854559ab8d6412ebf0a9615a949&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b242c81237407e520d835a20e3cc5dc4</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768543007</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="H. Taichui">
  <data key="d0">H. Taichui</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">H. Taichui is an organism, likely a parasite, whose metacercariae are detected in epidemiological surveys.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3d9595b06856e474a44aa9b2a3ed95a7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538873</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Infections In Fish Hosts">
  <data key="d0">Infections In Fish Hosts</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Infections in fish hosts refer to the presence of parasites like O. viverrini and H. taichui within fish.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3d9595b06856e474a44aa9b2a3ed95a7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538873</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Fish Hosts">
  <data key="d0">Fish Hosts</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Fish hosts are aquatic animals that can harbor infections, specifically metacercariae of certain parasites.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3d9595b06856e474a44aa9b2a3ed95a7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538874</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Mixed O. Taichui Infections">
  <data key="d0">Mixed O. Taichui Infections</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Mixed O. Taichui infections refer to the presence of multiple O. Taichui parasites within a host, diagnosable using PCR-RFLP profiles.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3d9595b06856e474a44aa9b2a3ed95a7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538874</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Farmers">
  <data key="d0">Farmers</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Farmers are a group of people whose education and practices, such as avoiding raw fish feeding and performing anthelmintic treatment, are needed in integrated FZT control programs.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d8aa5349e9d9a7250967a911875a6063</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538925</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Raw Fish">
  <data key="d0">Raw Fish</data>
  <data key="d1">naturalobject</data>
  <data key="d2">Raw fish is a food item that farmers are educated to avoid feeding to animals within integrated FZT control programs.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d8aa5349e9d9a7250967a911875a6063</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538925</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Anthelmintic Treatment">
  <data key="d0">Anthelmintic Treatment</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Anthelmintic treatment is a regular medical procedure for dogs, cats, and pigs that farmers are educated to perform within integrated FZT control programs.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d8aa5349e9d9a7250967a911875a6063</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538925</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Integrated FZT Control Programs">
  <data key="d0">Integrated FZT Control Programs</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Integrated FZT control programs are comprehensive strategies that require specific education for farmers and regular animal treatments for effective control.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d8aa5349e9d9a7250967a911875a6063</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538925</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Recombinant GST">
  <data key="d0">Recombinant GST</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">A protein expressed in E. coli, suggested to be an effective diagnostic reagent for detecting antibodies against S. japonicum in buffaloes and a candidate protein for immunological diagnosis of bovine schistosomiasis.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-242cd5f8872ef5ebae9f67588eafd60b</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538967</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="E. Coli">
  <data key="d0">E. Coli</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">A bacterium used for expressing recombinant GST.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-242cd5f8872ef5ebae9f67588eafd60b</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538967</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Buffaloes">
  <data key="d0">Buffaloes</data>
  <data key="d1">creature</data>
  <data key="d2">Animals in which antibodies against S. japonicum are detected and which can be diagnosed for bovine schistosomiasis.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-242cd5f8872ef5ebae9f67588eafd60b</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538967</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Antibody Against S. Japonicum">
  <data key="d0">Antibody Against S. Japonicum</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">A specific antibody detected in buffaloes, indicating the presence of S. japonicum.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-242cd5f8872ef5ebae9f67588eafd60b</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538967</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Bovine Schistosomiasis">
  <data key="d0">Bovine Schistosomiasis</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A disease affecting buffaloes, for which immunological diagnosis is a potential method.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-242cd5f8872ef5ebae9f67588eafd60b</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538967</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Immunological Diagnosis">
  <data key="d0">Immunological Diagnosis</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A diagnostic method for bovine schistosomiasis, for which recombinant GST is considered a candidate protein.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-242cd5f8872ef5ebae9f67588eafd60b</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768538967</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="iELISA">
  <data key="d0">iELISA</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">An established method identified as useful for diagnosing S. japonicum infection in cattle. It can also be utilized in serological surveys.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2267b7d403708ba84d848c3e6ebdc424</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768539022</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="S. Japonicum Infection">
  <data key="d0">S. Japonicum Infection</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A disease in cattle that can be diagnosed using the iELISA method, and its prevalence can be mapped through serological surveys.&lt;SEP&gt;A parasitic infection.&lt;SEP&gt;S. Japonicum Infection is a medical condition for which LAMP was demonstrated to be effective for early diagnosis and evaluation of therapy effectiveness.&lt;SEP&gt;An infection whose prevalence is dramatically underestimated by microscopic-based techniques in water buffaloes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2267b7d403708ba84d848c3e6ebdc424&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b11119067a2d2bb4bacfe766355b9408&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-80b97f9e924421f7263d201cc76d061b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-12418866e7efdfc1aa9ada51674dfa7e</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768544641</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Serological Surveys">
  <data key="d0">Serological Surveys</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Surveys that can use the iELISA method to map out the prevalence of diseases like S. japonicum infection.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2267b7d403708ba84d848c3e6ebdc424</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768539022</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Disease Prevalence">
  <data key="d0">Disease Prevalence</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The measure of how widespread a disease, specifically S. japonicum infection, is, which can be mapped out using serological surveys.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2267b7d403708ba84d848c3e6ebdc424</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768539022</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Recombinant FBPA of S. Japonicum">
  <data key="d0">Recombinant FBPA of S. Japonicum</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">A specific form of FBPA derived from S. Japonicum, indicated as a useful diagnostic tool.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-213dd01df1213177a022c154bb9c179e</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1768539054</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="IgY-IMB-ELISA">
  <data key="d0">IgY-IMB-ELISA</data>
